Fig. 3
 illustrates FESEM images of as-synthesized all Pt-CQD composites at lower and higher magnifications. Fig. 3(a) illustrates FESEM images of Pt (5 cycles)-CQD composite at a low magnification wherein low-density Pt nanostructures were observed on the surface of the CQD modified electrode. High magnification FESEM image (Fig. 3(b)) reveals nearly spherical Pt nanoparticles (NPs) with the average sizes of ~39 nm at 5 cycles of electro-deposition of Pt on CQD which acted as the nucleation sites for subsequent generation of three dimensional Pt nanoflowers. Fig. 3 (c–d) exhibit FESEM images of Pt (10 cycles)-CQD composite which confirm the formation of three dimensional Pt nanoflowers with the average sizes of 150 nm. The as-obtained Pt nanoflowers are formed because of nano-petals (average size of 45 nm) growing anisotropically on CQD and thereby offering the high surface area for methanol electro-oxidation. When the electro-deposition cycles reached 15 as presented in Fig. 3(e–f), very high-density Pt nanoflowers were electro-deposited on the CQD coated electrode and the petals of Pt nanoflowers become larger and aggregated. Furthermore, since the sizes of CQD in 2–6 nm, any distinctive features of CQD were not observed in the FE-SEM images of all Pt-CQD composites as shown in Fig. 3. Nevertheless, the existence of Pt and CQD in the composite was ensured by the EDX, elemental mapping and XPS study (Figs. 4, 5

).
